document_data.Description:
''D&D Miniatures'' departed from previous miniature lines in that their miniatures were pre-painted,{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210410151507/https://www.belloflostsouls.net/2020/02/dd-a-history-in-miniatures-prime.html| title = D&D: A History In Miniatures  Prime | accessdate = 12-07-2024| date = 02-12-2020}}{{Cite digital book/Designers & Dragons: The 90s|181}} made of plastic, and sold in randomized blind box collectible packs.{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151003123329/http://archive.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/mi/20040520b | title = What Are D&D Miniatures?| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 20-05-2004}} and later, beginning with ''Dungeons of Dread'', statistics for 4{{th}} edition.{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080119015055/http://wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/mi/20080116a | title = D&D Miniatures Battle Rules: The New Rulebook Is Here!| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 16-01-2008}} Early on the side featuring the tabletop statistics also included the concept art sketch for the miniature.{{Cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091003224505/http://www.wizards.com/DnD/Article.aspx?x=dnd/4news/20081023 | title = D&D Miniatures Changes Explained| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 23-10-2008}}

[[File:D&D Miniatures Sizes.jpg|thumb|273px|''A line-up of miniatures of different scales. From left to right: Medium, Huge, Small, and Large.'']]
The miniatures of each set were divided into three rarities: common, uncommon, and rare.{{Cite dragon/311/Sneak Preview: D&D Miniatures|24}} Each rarity was denoted by a marking on the bottom of a miniature's base. Those of "rare" rarity were given far more attention to detail in their painting than other of lower rarities. In the last major set released for the line, ''Lords of Madness'', a fourth rarity was introduced &ndash; very rare.

For a short time between 2009 and 2010 sets were marketed under the names "Monster Manual" and "Player's Handbook Heroes". The former were partially blind randomized packs, with a single figure visible, while the latter were non-random and exclusively featured miniatures of the various playable races and character classes.{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100108011219/http://www.wizards.com/DnD/Article.aspx?x=dnd/mi/20081021 | title = D&D Miniatures Announcement: Packing Changes in 2009| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 21-10-2008}} For the last year of the line's lifespan, miniatures would revert to being sold in completely random blind boxes.{{Cite web | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100219105150/http://www.wizards.com/DnD/Article.aspx?x=dnd/4pod/20100212 | title = D&D Experience Roundup| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 12-02-2010}}

A roleplaying supplement was released in the line's debut year, the ''[[Miniatures Handbook]]'', for use with 3.5{{th}} edition. This supplement offered further advice on integrating miniatures into the tabletop game, as well as mass combat rules.

document_data.History:
In June of 2002, Wizards of the Coast announced on their website that they would be ceasing production of their ''Chainmail Miniatures Game'' come August and hinted at having a new miniatures game in the works that would utilize the ''Dungeons & Dragons'' brand.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090602170704/http://www.wizards.com/dnd/article.asp?x=minis/ch20020627x | title = Chainmail  Brand to Be Discontinued after August 2002| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 27-06-2002}} The replacement to Chainmail would eventually be revealed the next year as the ''D&D Miniatures'' line and game, as well as a supplement titled ''[[Miniatures Handbook]]''.{{Cite dragon/311/Sneak Preview: D&D Miniatures|22}} The ''D&D Miniatures'' game would be a simplified & streamlined version of ''Chainmail'', being primarily the work of designers [[Jonathan Tweet]], [[Rob Heinsoo]], and [[Skaff Elias]].

The miniature line's first announced entry would be the eighty-miniature set ''Harbinger'', to be released on September 26{{th}}, followed shortly thereafter by the ''Miniatures Handbook'' in October and the expansion ''Dragoneye'' in November to coincide with the release of ''[[Draconomicon: The Book of Dragons]]''. Even in this early stage Wizards announced their intentions to produce creatures from the ''Forgotten Realms'' campaign setting, as well as other settings like Eberron and Dragonlance.{{Cite dragon/311/Sneak Preview: D&D Miniatures|23}} In September, prior to the release of ''Harbinger'', [[Dragon magazine 311|''Dragon'' #311]] came out with a Sneak Preview article talking about the new miniatures list and came with a sample challenge for the skirmish game.<ref>{{Cite dragon/311/Sneak Preview: D&D Miniatures}}

In an interview with the ''Miniature Handbook's'' designers, posted on the Wizards of the Coast website on September 13{{th}}, Jonathan Tweet stated that the impetus behind the development of both the supplement and the ''D&D Miniatures'' line in general was repeated observations that miniatures seemed to be integral to the ''Dungeons & Dragons'' experience and they wanted to support players who utilized them.{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20031008194156/http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/ps/20030913a| title = Product Spotlight: D&D Miniatures Handbook Team Interview | accessdate = 12-07-2024| date = 13-09-2003}}

In 2006, the ''D&D Miniatures'' line began to strain under increasing costs of manufacturing, eventually leading Wizards of the Coast to make the decision to increase the price of packs.

In early 2008 it was announced that all subsequent releases of ''D&D Miniatures'' would be designed for use with 4{{th}} edition, beginning with the set ''Dungeons of Dread'' in April, and that all existing miniatures would receive new stat-cards making them compatible with the new edition. This would be preceded by the set ''Desert of Desolation'' in January, which notably featured every monster that was to appear in the upcoming ''[[Monster Manual 4th edition|Monster Manual]]''. The ''D&D Miniatures Game'' in turn would received revisions to maintain continuity with the new rules.

Later in October of that same year, Wizards of the Coast announced their decision to change how ''D&D Miniatures'' were packaged, now intending to sell sets in packs subtitled ''Monster Manual'' and ''Player's Handbook Heroes'',{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210410151507/https://www.belloflostsouls.net/2020/02/dd-a-history-in-miniatures-prime.html| title = D&D: A History In Miniatures  Prime | accessdate = 12-07-2024| date = 02-12-2020}}

At ''[[wikipedia:Winter Fantasy|D&D Experience 2010]]'', Wizards of the Coast announced that they would be ceasing the division of sets into ''Monster Manual'' and ''Player's Handbook Heroes'' packs, as well as their decision to revert back to their prior method of packaging miniatures in entirely randomized packs.

On January 12, 2011, Wizards of the Coast announced on their official website the immediate end of the ''D&D Miniatures'' line, ending with the set ''Lords of Madness''. They clarified their intentions to continue releasing special collector's sets for a time and to repurpose their stock for other products, such as subsequent releases in the ''D&D Adventure System'' line,{{cite web| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110114093821/http://www.wizards.com/dnd/Article.aspx?x=dnd/dramp/2011January | title = D&D Miniatures Battle Rules: The New Rulebook Is Here!| accessdate = 21-07-2024| date = 12-01-2011}} ''[[Wrath of Ashardalon (board game)|Wrath of Ashardalon]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Drizzt Board Game|The Legend of Drizzt]]''.{{fact}}
